# Vendored from https://github.com/eyereasoner/eye/blob/master/reasoning/backward/backward.n3
# Unmodified.
#
# BLOCKED (see manifest.json "status": "ignored"): EYE proves this
# goal-directed, seeding the backward rule with the concrete query
# `5 :moreInterestingThan 3` (see backward-query.n3 upstream) and working
# backward to check `5 math:greaterThan 3`. This crate's engine is purely
# forward-chaining: the `<=` rule desugars to the forward rule
# `{?X math:greaterThan ?Y} => {?X :moreInterestingThan ?Y}`, but with no
# facts providing concrete `?X`/`?Y` candidates to iterate over, forward
# evaluation of `?X math:greaterThan ?Y` over an empty/var-only pattern never
# binds anything -- there is no query/goal-injection mechanism to seed `5`
# and `3` as the values to test, the way EYE's query file does.
@prefix math: <http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/math#>.
@prefix log: <http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/log#>.
@prefix : <http://example.org/#>.

{
    ?X :moreInterestingThan ?Y.
} <= {
    ?X math:greaterThan ?Y.
}.
